---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Formula from '../../components/Formula.astro';
import WorkedExample from '../../components/WorkedExample.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/site';

const snellenRows: [string, string, string, string][] = [
  ['20/20', '1.0', '0.0', '1.0'],
  ['20/25', '1.25', '0.1', '0.8'],
  ['20/32', '1.6', '0.2', '0.63'],
  ['20/40', '2.0', '0.3', '0.5'],
  ['20/50', '2.5', '0.4', '0.4'],
  ['20/63', '3.15', '0.5', '0.32'],
  ['20/80', '4.0', '0.6', '0.25'],
  ['20/100', '5.0', '0.7', '0.2'],
  ['20/200', '10.0', '1.0', '0.1'],
];

const references = [
  'American Academy of Ophthalmology, Vision Screening for Infants and Children (2022)',
  'AAPOS uniform guidelines for instrument-based pediatric vision screen validation (2021, JAAPOS)',
  'US Preventive Services Task Force, Vision in Children Ages 6 Months to 5 Years: Screening',
  'Levitt H. (1971), Transformed up-down methods in psychoacoustics, JASA',
  'Pediatric Eye Disease Investigator Group (PEDIG) amblyopia treatment studies',
  'ISO/IEC 7810 (ID-1 card dimensions)',
];
---

<Layout
  title="The Science & Math"
  description="The visual-angle geometry, logMAR scale, screen calibration, and adaptive-staircase statistics that Sight Scout's activity design is built on, shown with the actual math and worked examples."
>
  <h1>The science and math behind Sight Scout.</h1>
  <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-lg text-ink/85">
    Sight Scout's activity design borrows from a century of visual-acuity science: the same
    geometry, scales, and statistics behind professional eye charts. This page shows the
    actual math, because you shouldn't have to trust a tool for your child that won't show
    its work. (To be clear: this describes our activity design. It doesn't make Sight Scout
    a diagnostic test, and it isn't one.)
  </p>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Visual angle: size only means something with distance.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Vision science measures detail not in millimeters but in <strong>visual angle</strong>,
      which is how large something looks from where you stand. A shape's visual angle θ
      depends on its physical height <em>h</em> and viewing distance <em>d</em>:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\theta = 2\\arctan\\!\\left(\\frac{h}{2d}\\right) \\approx \\frac{h}{d}\\ \\text{(radians, for small angles)}'}
      label="theta equals two times arc-tangent of h over two d, approximately equal to h over d, in radians, for small angles"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      The standard reference: a person with "20/20" vision can just resolve detail spanning
      <strong>1 arcminute</strong>, which is 1/60 of a degree. Standard optotypes (the shapes
      on eye charts) are built on a 5×5 grid. The whole shape spans <strong>5 arcminutes</strong>
      at threshold, and its critical detail, a stroke or a gap, spans <strong>1 arcminute</strong>.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-6">
      <WorkedExample>
        <p>How big is a "20/20-sized" optotype on a screen 60 cm away?</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          θ = 5 arcmin = 5/60 degree = 0.001454 rad. h ≈ d·θ = 600 mm × 0.001454 ≈
          <strong>0.87 mm</strong>, about the thickness of a credit card. Its critical gap is a
          fifth of that, roughly 0.17 mm, smaller than a single pixel on many screens. This is
          exactly why calibration and honest engineering limits matter (see below).
        </p>
      </WorkedExample>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Snellen, logMAR, and decimal: the scales.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      "20/40" means this person resolves at 20 feet what a reference eye resolves at 40. The
      ratio gives the <strong>minimum angle of resolution</strong> (MAR) in arcminutes.
      Research settings work with its logarithm, <strong>logMAR</strong>, and some countries
      use decimal acuity. All three are the same information:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\text{MAR} = \\frac{\\text{denominator}}{\\text{numerator}}\\ \\text{arcmin}, \\qquad \\text{logMAR} = \\log_{10}(\\text{MAR}), \\qquad \\text{decimal} = 10^{-\\text{logMAR}}'}
      label="M A R equals denominator over numerator in arcminutes; log MAR equals log base ten of MAR; decimal acuity equals ten to the power of negative log MAR"
    />
    <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-line">
      <table class="w-full border-collapse text-left text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col" class="bg-sky px-4 py-3 font-bold">Snellen</th>
            <th scope="col" class="bg-sky px-4 py-3 font-bold">MAR (arcmin)</th>
            <th scope="col" class="bg-sky px-4 py-3 font-bold">logMAR</th>
            <th scope="col" class="bg-sky px-4 py-3 font-bold">Decimal</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {snellenRows.map(([snellen, mar, logmar, decimal], i) => (
            <tr class={i % 2 === 1 ? 'bg-white/60' : ''}>
              <td class="border-t border-line px-4 py-2.5">{snellen}</td>
              <td class="border-t border-line px-4 py-2.5">{mar}</td>
              <td class="border-t border-line px-4 py-2.5">{logmar}</td>
              <td class="border-t border-line px-4 py-2.5">{decimal}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      logMAR is the scale modern charts (ETDRS) use because it makes lines evenly spaced:
      each line is 0.1 logMAR, and with five optotypes per line, each optotype is worth 0.02.
      That allows scoring by the shape, not just by the line:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\text{score} = \\text{logMAR}_{\\text{best line}} + 0.02 \\times (\\text{shapes missed on it})'}
      label="score equals the log MAR of the best line read, plus zero point zero two times the number of shapes missed on that line"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Sight Scout's activity engine works in logMAR internally for the same reason: every
      answer moves the estimate by a known, even amount.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Putting shapes on a screen: calibration.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      A screen only knows pixels; the math needs millimeters. If the device reports its true
      pixel density in pixels per inch, the scale factor comes free:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'s = \\frac{25.4\\ \\text{mm}}{\\text{PPI}}\\ \\text{mm/px}'}
      label="s equals twenty-five point four millimeters divided by pixels per inch, giving millimeters per pixel"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Reported density isn't always trustworthy, so there's a physical fallback: match an
      on-screen rectangle to a standard bank card (ISO/IEC 7810 ID-1, exactly
      <strong>85.60 mm × 53.98 mm</strong>, the same everywhere in the world). If the matched
      rectangle is <em>p</em> pixels wide, then the scale and the on-screen shape height
      follow directly:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'s = \\frac{85.60\\ \\text{mm}}{p}\\ \\text{mm/px} \\qquad\\Rightarrow\\qquad h_{px} = \\frac{d \\cdot 2\\tan(\\theta/2)}{s}'}
      label="s equals eighty-five point six millimeters divided by p, in millimeters per pixel; h sub p x equals d times two tan of theta over two, divided by s"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Distance is the other half of calibration. The activity assumes a set distance, setup
      makes it part of the mission briefing, and the error math below is why the app is fussy
      about it.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-6">
      <WorkedExample>
        <p>
          Tablet with s = 0.096 mm/px (a common 264 ppi panel), child at 1.5 m, target size
          20/40 (MAR 2 arcmin, so the shape spans 10 arcmin = 0.002909 rad):
        </p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          h = 1500 × 0.002909 ≈ <strong>4.36 mm</strong>, which is 4.36 / 0.096 ≈
          <strong>45 px</strong>. Comfortably renderable. At sensible distances the geometry
          works out.
        </p>
      </WorkedExample>
    </div>

    <div class="card mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-lg">Try the geometry yourself.</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink/60">
        A calculator, not a vision test. It converts a target size and distance into
        millimeters and pixels, nothing more.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <div>
          <label for="calc-distance" class="text-sm font-semibold">Viewing distance</label>
          <input id="calc-distance" type="range" min="40" max="300" value="150" step="5" class="mt-2 w-full" />
          <p id="calc-distance-out" class="mt-1 font-mono text-sm text-ink/70"></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="calc-snellen" class="text-sm font-semibold">Target size</label>
          <select id="calc-snellen" class="mt-2 w-full rounded-xl border border-line bg-cream px-3 py-2">
            <option>20/20</option>
            <option>20/25</option>
            <option>20/32</option>
            <option selected>20/40</option>
            <option>20/50</option>
            <option>20/63</option>
            <option>20/80</option>
            <option>20/100</option>
            <option>20/200</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="calc-ppi" class="text-sm font-semibold">Screen density (ppi)</label>
          <input id="calc-ppi" type="number" min="50" max="1000" value="264" class="mt-2 w-full rounded-xl border border-line bg-cream px-3 py-2" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <p id="calc-result" class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-sky px-4 py-3 text-[15px]" aria-live="polite"></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>The distance error budget.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      If the child sits closer than the math assumes, every shape is effectively bigger than
      intended, and the session flatters. The distortion has a simple form in logMAR:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\Delta\\text{logMAR} = \\log_{10}\\!\\left(\\frac{d_{\\text{assumed}}}{d_{\\text{actual}}}\\right)'}
      label="delta log MAR equals log base ten of assumed distance over actual distance"
    />
    <div class="mt-6">
      <WorkedExample>
        <p>Assumed 150 cm, actual 120 cm:</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          Δ = log₁₀(150/120) ≈ <strong>0.097, almost exactly one full chart line</strong> of
          flattery. This one equation is why the app is strict about setup and distance, and
          why "hold the phone wherever" vision apps deserve your skepticism.
        </p>
      </WorkedExample>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Engineering limits: what a screen can honestly render.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      The critical detail of an optotype is 1/5 of its height. For that detail to be
      trustworthy it should span at least about 2 device pixels; below that, anti-aliasing is
      deciding what your child sees, not you. So each device and distance combination has a
      <strong> smallest honest size</strong>:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'h_{\\min} = 5 \\times 2 \\times s \\qquad \\theta_{\\min} \\approx \\frac{h_{\\min}}{d}'}
      label="h sub min equals five times two times s; theta sub min is approximately equal to h sub min over d"
    />
    <div class="mt-6">
      <WorkedExample>
        <p>Phone with s = 0.06 mm/px at 1.5 m:</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          h_min = 0.6 mm, so θ_min ≈ 0.0004 rad ≈ 1.4 arcmin ≈ logMAR 0.13. Sizes near 20/25
          and finer aren't honestly renderable on that device at that distance, and the
          activity refuses to pretend otherwise. Sight Scout computes this limit per device
          and stays above it.
        </p>
      </WorkedExample>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Shapes for pre-readers.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Letter charts assume literacy. For young children, established optotype families use a
      small set of symbols or a single rotatable shape, answered by <strong>matching</strong>
      (point at the same shape on a card or screen) rather than naming. That makes each round
      a 4-alternative choice with a known 25% guess rate, which the statistics account for.
      Mature pediatric optotypes are also designed to blur equally, so no shape is "easier"
      than another. Sight Scout's shape set follows the same design principles.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Amblyopia research adds one more wrinkle: <strong>crowding</strong>. An amblyopic visual
      system struggles disproportionately when shapes are flanked by neighbors. Professional
      pediatric charts surround optotypes with crowding bars for exactly this reason, and
      Sight Scout's activity presents its shapes with playful flanking elements that do the
      same job.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2 id="the-adaptive-staircase" class="scroll-mt-28">The adaptive staircase.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Instead of marching through a fixed chart, the activity adapts. A classic
      <strong> transformed up-down staircase</strong> makes the shape smaller after two
      consecutive correct answers and larger after one miss ("2-down-1-up"). That rule
      converges near the size a player gets right 70.7% of the time:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\text{2-down-1-up} \\Rightarrow p_{\\text{target}} = \\sqrt{0.5} \\approx 0.707'}
      label="the two-down-one-up staircase converges toward a target probability equal to the square root of one half, approximately seventy point seven percent"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Why not just count right answers? Because four-year-olds guess, and sometimes they get
      lucky. With four choices, the chance of a lucky streak shrinks fast:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'P(k\\ \\text{lucky in a row}) = 0.25^{k} \\qquad 0.25^{3} \\approx 1.6\\%'}
      label="the probability of k lucky guesses in a row equals zero point two five to the power k; three in a row is about one point six percent"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      So single flukes barely move the estimate, and streaks that would fool the math are
      rare. Underneath, performance at any size is modeled by a psychometric function: the
      probability of a correct answer rises smoothly from the guess rate toward certainty as
      shapes get larger. A standard form is the Weibull:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\psi(x) = \\gamma + (1 - \\gamma - \\lambda)\\left(1 - e^{-(x/\\alpha)^{\\beta}}\\right)'}
      label="psi of x equals gamma, plus the quantity one minus gamma minus lambda, times the quantity one minus e to the power negative x over alpha, raised to the power beta"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Here γ is the guess rate (0.25 for a 4-choice task), λ is a small lapse rate (kids get
      distracted, and the model forgives them for it), α is the threshold and β the slope.
      The staircase estimates the threshold from its <strong>reversals</strong>, the moments
      where the trend flips from getting harder to getting easier or back. Averaging the
      sizes at the last N reversals gives a stable estimate in remarkably few trials:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\hat{\\alpha} = \\frac{1}{N}\\sum_{i=1}^{N} x_{\\text{rev}_i}'}
      label="the threshold estimate alpha-hat equals the average of the sizes at the last N reversals"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      That efficiency matters when your participant is four. For the child, all of it
      disappears into a game that feels just tricky enough: never boringly easy, never
      dishearteningly hard.
    </p>

    <div class="card mt-8">
      <h3 class="text-lg">Watch the staircase work.</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink/60">
        The player below is simulated code with a preset, hidden threshold. Nothing about you
        is measured. Each run: filled teal dots are correct answers, open coral dots are
        misses, gold rings are reversals. The gold dashed line is the truth; the teal dashed
        line is what the math recovered from a couple dozen trials.
      </p>
      <svg
        id="sim-chart"
        viewBox="0 0 640 300"
        class="mt-6 w-full"
        role="img"
        aria-label="Staircase simulation chart"
      ></svg>
      <p id="sim-caption" class="mt-4 rounded-xl bg-sky px-4 py-3 text-[15px]" aria-live="polite"></p>
      <button id="sim-run" type="button" class="btn btn-primary mt-5">Run another simulated player</button>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16">
    <h2>Two eyes, one comparison.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Amblyopia is usually a story about <strong>asymmetry</strong>, which is why each eye
      plays separately while the other rests under the patch. The quantity of interest is the
      interocular difference:
    </p>
    <Formula
      tex={'\\text{IOD} = \\left|\\ \\text{logMAR}_{\\text{left}} - \\text{logMAR}_{\\text{right}}\\ \\right|'}
      label="the interocular difference equals the absolute value of left-eye log MAR minus right-eye log MAR"
    />
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-ink/85">
      Clinical referral criteria, used by professionals and cited here for education, show
      why this number matters. Commonly used pediatric guidelines treat both an
      age-referenced acuity level (roughly 20/50 at age 3, 20/40 at age 4, 20/32 at 5 and up)
      and an interocular difference of <strong>two or more lines, meaning IOD ≥ 0.2 logMAR</strong>,
      as reasons for a comprehensive exam, per AAPOS and AAO guidance. Sight Scout's per-eye
      design exists so its plain-language observations can reflect the same kind of asymmetry
      professionals care about, always as a reason to visit a professional and never as a
      diagnosis.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-16 border-t border-line pt-8">
    <h2 class="text-lg">References</h2>
    <ul class="mt-4 flex flex-col gap-2 text-sm text-ink/70">
      {references.map((r) => <li>{r}</li>)}
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-ink/60">
      Unfamiliar term? Everything on this page is defined in the <a href={url('glossary/')} class="font-semibold text-teal hover:text-teal-dark">glossary</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <script>
    import { initSizeCalculator } from '../../scripts/size-calculator';
    import { initStaircaseSim } from '../../scripts/staircase-sim';
    initSizeCalculator();
    initStaircaseSim();
  </script>
</Layout>
